<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,975,2019]" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">
<emphasis box="[199,361,976,999]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Wing venation</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[378,461,975,1000]" captionStart="FIGURE 12 – 15" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1797,1819]" captionTargetBox="[338,1274,950,1768]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[302,1285,940,1775]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 12 – 15. Wing venation of Mimaporia hmong and detail of forewing venation in the three possible sister genera. Arrows indicates the differences of M 1 - M 2 vein among the taxa. 12. M. hmong. Scale bar = 1 cm; 13. Burmeia leesi; 14. Chatamla flavescens; 15. Parabraxas davidi. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556283/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Forewing: Sc ending at around one-half of costa from base. R1 free, separated from R2+R3+R4 stem. R5 and M1 stalked. Discal cell closed. Discocellular vein M1-M2 strongly bent and much longer than M2-M3. Hindwing: Rs and M1 connate. Discal cell closed. Discocellular vein M1-M2 bent and much longer than M2-M3, shaped as that of forewing. 3A present, as long as half of 1A+2A.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,975,2019]" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">
<emphasis box="[199,426,1130,1155]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Pregenital abdomen</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[442,568,1130,1155]" captionStart="FIGURES 16 – 19" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1376,1399]" captionTargetBox="[477,1111,388,1337]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[462,1125,373,1355]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 16 – 19. Pregenital abdomen of Mimaporia hmong. 16. Androconial organ, lateral view; 17. Sternum A 2, ventral view; 18. The concave condition at anterolateral sternum A 2. 19. Tergum A 8. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556284/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Fig. 16–19</figureCitation>
). Androconial hair brush long, lying in longitudinal furrow by lateral edge of sterna A2 and A3.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,975,2019]" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">
<emphasis box="[209,377,1202,1227]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[396,527,1202,1227]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 24" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1856,1879]" captionTargetBox="[320,1259,1490,1835]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[313,1273,1479,1835]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 24. Male genitalia of Mimaporia hmong. 20 - 21. Genitalia capsule in lateral (20) and ventral (21) view. 22. Magnified area, showing costula. 23 - 24. Aedeagus. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556285/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Fig. 20–24</figureCitation>
). Uncus bent downwards apically in lateral view, with a well indicated suture between it and tegumen. Gnathos absent. Subscaphium present, slightly sclerotized. Costula present at conjunction between tegumen and vinculum, strongly sclerotized with surface granulate. Valva with costa slightly convex and sclerotized, a rounded apex and a densely setose inner surface. Praesacculus strongly sclerotized and protruding, apically v-shaped. Sacculus sclerotized. Saccus short, rectangular in ventral view. Juxta nearly U-shaped in ventral view. Aedeagus with a spoon-like apex and a strongly sclerotized shaft; cornutus absent; coecum absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,975,2019]" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">
<emphasis box="[199,391,1418,1443]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[407,532,1418,1443]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 – 26" captionStartId="9.[151,264,908,931]" captionTargetBox="[389,1187,193,832]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[340,1247,171,887]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 25 – 26. Female genitalia of Mimaporia hmong. 25. Lateral view. 26. Ventral view. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556286/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Fig. 25–26</figureCitation>
). Papillae anales slightly sclerotized, elongated, elliptical at end. Ostium bursae wide as antrum. Lamella antevaginalis rectangular ventrally, with lateral sides hooked and strongly sclerotized. Lamella postvaginalis broad, sclerotized, granulate at posterior part, edge dentate and convex. Apophyses thin and long. Length of posterior apophysis more than 2 times that of anterior apophysis. Antrum membranous. Ductus bursae very short, membranous. Ductus seminalis arising from ductus bursae close to antrum. Corpus bursae spherical, membranous. Signum absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="546" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,975,2019]" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1634,1659]" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic name refers to the potential co-mimicry with 
<taxonomicName box="[1016,1094,1635,1658]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Aporia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1016,1094,1635,1658]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Aporia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
butterflies (
<taxonomicName box="[1235,1330,1634,1659]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pieridae</taxonomicName>
) because both genera have orange/yellow tegulae and many stripes and dots lying on dark ground colour in both fore- and hindwings.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="546" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,975,2019]" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1742,1767]" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Appearance of 
<taxonomicName box="[503,629,1743,1766]" class="Insecta" family="Epicopeiidae" genus="Mimaporia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis box="[503,629,1743,1766]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Mimaporia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[844,912,1743,1766]" class="Insecta" family="Epicopeiidae" genus="Nossa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[844,912,1743,1766]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Nossa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in particular 
<taxonomicName box="[1074,1248,1742,1767]" class="Insecta" family="Epicopeiidae" genus="Nossa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palaearctica">
<emphasis box="[1074,1248,1742,1767]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">N. palaearctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The new genus can be distinguished from other epicopeiid genera but 
<emphasis box="[766,863,1780,1803]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Burmeia</emphasis>
by an uncommon trait, the discocellular vein M2– M3 significantly shorter than M1–M2 (
<figureCitation box="[603,731,1814,1839]" captionStart="FIGURE 12 – 15" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1797,1819]" captionTargetBox="[338,1274,950,1768]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[302,1285,940,1775]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 12 – 15. Wing venation of Mimaporia hmong and detail of forewing venation in the three possible sister genera. Arrows indicates the differences of M 1 - M 2 vein among the taxa. 12. M. hmong. Scale bar = 1 cm; 13. Burmeia leesi; 14. Chatamla flavescens; 15. Parabraxas davidi. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556283/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Fig. 12–15</figureCitation>
). Although absence of gnathos and an extending longitudinal furrow, sharing with 
<emphasis box="[397,494,1852,1875]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Burmeia</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[556,729,1850,1875]" class="Insecta" family="Epicopeiidae" genus="Psychostrophia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[556,729,1850,1875]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Psychostrophia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are also found in 
<taxonomicName box="[956,1082,1852,1875]" class="Insecta" family="Epicopeiidae" genus="Mimaporia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis box="[956,1082,1852,1875]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Mimaporia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a pair of strongly sclerotized costula, a rectangular lamella antevaginalis and a broad lamella postvaginalis can discriminate 
<taxonomicName box="[1208,1334,1887,1910]" class="Insecta" family="Epicopeiidae" genus="Mimaporia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis box="[1208,1334,1887,1910]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Mimaporia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the two genera. The molecular phylogenies show that 
<taxonomicName box="[716,842,1924,1947]" class="Insecta" family="Epicopeiidae" genus="Mimaporia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis box="[716,842,1924,1947]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Mimaporia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
associates with either 
<taxonomicName box="[1095,1206,1922,1947]" class="Insecta" family="Epicopeiidae" genus="Chatamla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1095,1206,1922,1947]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Chatamla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName box="[1243,1375,1922,1947]" class="Insecta" family="Epicopeiidae" genus="Parabraxas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1243,1375,1922,1947]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Parabraxas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1980,2002]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,908,1950]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,905,1956]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Phylogenetic hypothesis from maximum likelihood analysis shows the inter-generic relationship between Mimaporia and Chatamla. Tree robustness is evaluated by rapid bootstrap. Values larger than 50 % are labelled on branch." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556279/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[180,196,1959,1983]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1694,1716]" captionTargetBox="[165,1416,557,1669]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[165,1417,555,1675]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Phylogenetic hypothesis from Bayesian analysis yields the inter-generic relationship between Mimaporia and Parabraxas. Posterior probability larger than 80 % are labelled on branch." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/556280/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">2</figureCitation>
), which are suggested as sister group in 
<bibRefCitation author="Minet" box="[662,815,1958,1983]" pageId="9" pageNumber="546" refString="Minet, J. (2003) The Epicopeiidae: phylogeny and a redefinition, with the description of new taxa (Lepidoptera: Drepanoidea). Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France, 38, 463 - 487. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00379271.2002.10697355" type="journal article" year="2003">Minet (2003)</bibRefCitation>
. However, we find no morphological traits connecting 
<taxonomicName box="[151,277,1996,2019]" class="Insecta" family="Epicopeiidae" genus="Mimaporia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis box="[151,277,1996,2019]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="546">Mimaporia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to the two potential sister taxa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
